For a long time, the parks in British Columbia were at the top of the places that I wanted to see. A few summers ago, I finally got the chance to take a road trip from the East Coast out to BC.

After about 40 hours total of driving, I pulled into Yoho National Park just before dawn. The first thing that I saw was the sunrise on this lake, and the long trip was more than worth it.

I love Zion, and this time of year is my favorite time to go. In my opinion, it’s the best season to visit.

The park is a lot quieter, and you can drive your own car into the canyon without having to shuttle. With the exception of the Narrows and Angel’s Landing, it’s really an ideal time for most of the other hikes in the park. Plus, the golden hours at dawn and dusk are more intense, making for a great contrast between the enormous walls glowing orange and the darker, snow-covered canyon floors below. It’s definitely my favorite time of year for photography in the park.

I’ve gone out there the past two winters, hoping to make it back for a third at some point.

Photos from a hike to the roof of Africa.

I've gotten a few messages about this mountain lately, so I thought I'd make an informative post about what hiking Kilimanjaro is like for those interested. 

Kilimanjaro is unique in that it's the tallest peak on the African continent, and rises as a single massif from the plains of Tanzania. At 19,340 feet, it's the tallest freestanding mountain in the world. 

It's also one of the few high peaks in the world that can be ascended without specialized skills or mountaineering equipment. I describe it as more of a backpacking trip, or just a long hike at altitude, rather than a big mountain climb. 

That said, it makes for a world-class multi-day trek. What's really cool about the hike is that it passes through five different ecological zones. You start by hiking through the cultivation zone, where farmers grow coffee beans in the volcanic soil. Next, you're hiking through montane forest, where we saw colubus monkeys swinging from the canopies. Higher, the moorlands take over, and Giant Groundsels (pictured third in this set), grow out of open fields. These prehistoric plants look can only be found on Kilimanjaro and Mt. Kenya. After that, you're hiking through barren alpine desert, and finally, you reach the higher altitudes where snow and ice persists year round. The summit is remarkable--on one side you're looking down into a huge volcanic crater, and on the other, the plains of East Africa go on forever. It was one of the more impressive summit views that I've seen.

Because you can just walk up it, I found Kilimanjaro to be much less difficult than other mountains of similar altitude. It still shouldn't be underestimated, with altitude sickness being the main concern on this mountain. I would say go slow, drink lots of water, and don't be afraid about turning around if symptoms of altitude sickness persist. It does get a lot colder at the top than many people expect, so lots of layers and a good sleeping bag help.

In my opinion, Kilimanjaro is more than worth hiking for the variation of what you get to see and experience along the route. I met some great people, and I look back on that trip with fond memories.

Photos from a hike to the bottom of the Grand Canyon and back.

A couple of years ago in the wintertime, I hiked down to the Colorado River and back up to the South Rim of the Grand Canyon in one long day. It was a really cool experience, and definitely one of the most spectacular single day hikes that I’ve done in the US. 

Although there was quite a bit of snow at the top of the trail to navigate, I found February to be a good time of year to hike it. The extreme heat that makes the trail risky in the summertime just wasn’t a factor then.

I look back on that day with fond memories, and I’d like to go back and hike the canyon from the South to the North Rim someday soon.

Probably my favorite place to catch a desert sunset.

Artists Palette in Death Valley is hidden behind an unassuming, mostly barren, yellowish landscape. You drive for miles, turn the corner, and all of a sudden you’re looking at these brilliant rainbow colors in the rocks.

The colors are created by volcanic deposits rich in compounds like iron oxides and chlorite, which is what causes the rainbow effect. 

It’s worth visiting any time of day, but I’ve found that the minutes right before the sunset are when the colors are the most vibrant.

I’ll never forget this morning in Glacier National Park.

It was still dark outside when I rolled out of my tent to take photos of the sunrise. The park was covered in dense, heavy fog, and I figured that it probably wouldn’t be much of a morning for photography.

I made coffee, and sat by the lake for a while. Very slowly, the fog started to lift with the first light of the day. Everything glowed soft white and yellow for a few minutes, and the silhouettes of the mountains were just visible. The whole scene was spectacular, and pretty surreal.

Just as I was about to start hiking, I looked up to see these riders on horseback crossing the bridge through the fog. I thought it would make for a cool photo.

It was a few years ago now, but when I look at this picture it brings back good memories of Montana, the West, and that morning in Glacier.

I feel lucky to live so close to this place. 

Some fun facts—The state of NY created Adirondack Park in 1892. The park contains six-million acres, making it the largest publicly protected area in the contiguous United States. It’s pretty wild when you think about it—the Adirondacks covers one-fifth of NYS, is equal in size to the state of Vermont, and is larger than Yosemite, Everglades, Grand Canyon, and Yellowstone National Parks combined. 

Which means, for me at least, that there’s a lot more to explore up there this year. Looking forward to it.

I haven’t been on social media as much lately, so I figured I’d post a little update. I’ve been racking up a lot of overtime hours at my regular job, and putting a lot of effort into photography afterwards. Some exciting things are starting to come together—I have a couple local photography shows, and I’m partnering with a some air bnbs and state tourism departments, which should make for a few cool trips and opportunities in the next few months.

That aside, I’ve just been focused on less screen time and living in the moment a little bit more, and starting to prepare for this big summer trip that’s coming together. It’s been on my mind a lot lately, and I’m really looking forward to it.

I do want to stay connected with my friends on this app, and continue to share the photos I’ve been working on. Today I thought I’d challenge myself to edit and share five photos that I haven’t touched before, and I started with the Canadian Rockies. 

These five were taken in Banff, Jasper, and Yoho National Parks. 🏔

Deep blues in Banff.

I’m a big fan of traveling back to the same places so that you can really get to know them over a period of time, and to see things that you might have missed the last time.

That said, a lot of my favorite memories are from when I experienced a National Park or a new country for the first time. 

I took this video on my first trip to Banff in 2016. I’ve been back many times since then, but driving up the Icefields Parkway for the first time with two of my best friends and seeing the mountains and turquoise alpine lakes—having never been there before—is a feeling that I won’t forget.

Having first-time experiences like that and exploring and learning about new places, to me, is what makes travel worthwhile.

To this day, this was one of the most remarkable views that I’ve caught in Glacier. 

I’d been driving for four days by the time I finally arrived in the park, so I was pretty happy to make it there just in time for sunset on that particular July evening.

I still had a long way to drive until I got to the campground, but I sat on top of my car and took in those colors until it got dark.
This trail is my first stop every time I travel to Montana. 🏔

Photos from a solo journey that I took into Wyoming’s Wind River Range.

The Winds made for one of the cooler trips that I’ve taken. They’re one of the more remote and rugged mountain ranges in the lower 48, and exceptionally scenic. These mountains are home to 19 of Wyoming’s 20 highest peaks, and the most extensive glacial network anywhere in the US Rockies.

While I was hiking and camping, I had this real feeling of being alone and out there. The isolation is part of what makes the Winds special. There’s no cell service, and I only encountered one or two other people along the trail. I did see a bull moose, elk, and black bear though, which was pretty cool.

If I was going to go back to the Wind River Range, I’d go with a group of friends and do a multi-day backpacking trip. I didn’t venture nearly as far into the backcountry as I would have liked, just out of an abundance of caution being by myself. So I still think about that place often, and have a lot more to see there. All in all, it a was definitely a rich experience, and I’m looking forward to whenever I can make it back.

More times than not, the summit was covered in clouds and fog. But when Rainier was visible, I was always impressed by the way it dwarfed the Space Needle and Seattle skyline.

Having spent so many mornings looking out at nothing but grey, I was pretty stoked when Tori and I went back to hike in the park last summer and caught a day like this. I tried to appreciate the view, because I know how few and far between they can be for most of the year.

I’m definitely looking forward to getting back out there on our big trip this summer, whatever plans the weather has for us.

The feeling you get when you’re in the mountains, and the landscape is so expansive that it makes you feel small by compassion.

Whenever I’m in an immense landscape like that, I find that feeling sort of comforting for some reason. It reminds me that whatever’s been on my mind doesn’t matter too much in the scheme of things. That we’re part of something bigger than ourselves.

Places like that also tend to get me thinking about time in more of a geological sense, and how comparatively little of it we have. They remind me to live more fully and with intent while I can. 

(Or as Erik Dollard, or Andy Dufresne would say, to “get busy livin.”)

If you live on the East Coast, it can be a little tricky to find truly dark, starry skies for stargazing and nighttime photography. 

The good news is that there’s a place within a day’s drive that has some of the largest, darkest night skies in the eastern portion of the United States: West Virginia. (@wvtourism #almostheaven #wvtourismpartner.) 

In fact, just last year Travel + Leisure named the state as “the most under-the-radar stargazing destination in the U.S.” It’s home to one of the largest and darkest sky sheds east of the Mississippi, making it it the ideal spot to relax and soak in the beautiful, star-studded skies. 

Even more impressive, West Virginia is home to three official Dark Sky Parks, designated by the International Dark-Sky Association: Calvin Price State Forest, Droop Mountain Battlefield State Park, and Watoga State Park. These parks obtained official Dark Sky Status in October of 2021. 

We chose Watoga State Park and Calvin Price State Forest as our stargazing destinations. On the first night of our trip, we walked up to Watoga Lake just after sunset and watched as the night sky filled up with a million stars. We sat there on the picnic tables for a while just taking it all in; easily one of the starriest and best night skies I’ve seen, anywhere in my travels.

Our three-day itinerary for the Swiss Alps.🏔

Tori and I only had a few days to spend between the Azores and Ireland, so we decided to go to one of the most spectacular mountain ranges in Europe—the Swiss Alps.

Ideally, I would love to have weeks or months to spend exploring Switzerland, but sometimes when you’re traveling, it’s just not possible to get that kind of time. We just barely scratched the surface, but these are the places that we went and hiked to make the most out of our short time in the Swiss Alps:

1. Kleine Scheidegg: This was my favorite place that we went. You can take a scenic train ride from Grindelwald up to this mountain pass, and right from the Kleine Scheidegg train station there’s a whole network of hiking trails to check out. Insane views of Eiger, Monch, and Jungfrau the entire way.

2. Lake Oeschinen: You can take a gondola or hike from Kanderstag to get to this glacial blue lake. Again, there’s a number of trails from the gondola that take you directly to, or up above the lake. We opted to hike the panorama trail, skip the last gondola, and hike out at sunset. Great evening.

3. Lauterbrunnen: Has to be one of the most beautiful valleys in Europe. It kind of reminds me of being in Yosemite a little bit, surrounded by massive granite walls and cascading waterfalls. You can hike up to Wengen for some better views of the valley, or just walk around the town. We got to Lauterbrunnen before sunrise and more or less had the streets and lookouts to ourselves.

4. Lake Thun: An alpine lake in the Bernese Oberland near Interlaken. Our friends in the Emmantale (also another beautiful region that we went to), recommended driving up the eastern shores of the lake and visiting the medieval Oberhoften Castle. Beautiful place, but what we liked most was the cafe right next to the castle—Pier 17. One of the best places I’ve sat and had a coffee for sure.

5. Harder Kulm: At 4,000 feet, the Harder Kulm is the nearest mountain to Interlaken. There’s a great panoramic lookout from the top with views of Interlaken, the Eiger, Monch and Junfrau. It’s also a really good jumping off point for more serious hikes across the ridge from Harder Klum.

This past month on the road was important to me. I never know when I'll get the chance to do a trip like this again. So I've tried to be where my feet are, and to experience each day as fully as possible. This trip's been a lot of things--inspiring most of the time, a little exhausting at other times. I've tried to capture a few of those moments in these photos.

One of my goals out here was to put my heart into every photo that I take, and to keep moving forward with photography. There were a lot of late nights and early mornings spent waiting out storms, crawling out of the sleeping bag hours before dawn to go and shoot. I gave it my best, and I'm looking forward to going through the photos next month.

Probably the coolest waterfall I’ve seen, and one of the most beautiful in California.

Like a lot of places, Burney has grown in popularity over the years. It’s easy to get to, and you really don’t have to hike at all to see it. We got there early on a weekday though, and more or less had the place to ourselves. 

Definitely worth checking out next time you’re in Northern California.

Complete Guide to Hiking Indian Head🍁:

I’ve had a lot of questions about this particular hike—so here’s everything you need to know about hiking Indian Head, which is in my opinion, is one of the most spectacular fall hikes that you can do in the Northeast:

-A reservation for parking/access is required through the Adirondack Mountain Reserve to do this hike via Lake Road from May 1st through Oct. 31st. You can make reservations beginning April 17th at www.hikeamr.org. Permits are released two weeks in advance at midnight on the AMR website. Permits go quickly for the peak of fall, but if you’re quick with the refresh button at midnight, they’re definitely possible to get. If you don’t get one, it’s worth double-checking throughout the week as people often cancel.

-The hike itself is over 10 miles round-trip, and gains around 2,000 feet of elevation. The trail is relatively easy compared to a lot of other hikes in the High Peaks Region. It follows a dirt access road with a gradual incline for the first three miles, before branching upwards for a short but steep incline to the top. That said, it’s still important to double-check the weather, know what you’re comfortable with, and plan ahead as you would for any hike.

-Much of the trail is on private property, so dogs aren’t allowed unfortunately. There are no facilities along the trail, and as always, carry in/carry out, stick to the trail, and LNT. The trail can be done as an out-and-back, or as a loop hike with the scenic Gill Brook Trail.

-The view above Lower Ausable Lake, I think, is one of the most incredible views in NYS. It’s been called “Fjord Country in the ADKS,” and it does remind me a little bit of the fjord views back in Southeast Alaska or Norway. 

-For photography, I like to shoot this spot in the afternoon and sunset. The vista faces to the southwest, so you get the light illuminating the trees and foliage in the late afternoon and until sunset.

-It’s worth stopping by Rainbow Falls and the lakeshore on the way up or down—awesome views. 

-Have a great hike and enjoy. If there’s something I left out, or if you have any more specific questions, feel free to message me as always.

If you’re planning to travel to Switzerland, it’s definitely worth checking out these four lakes. The turquoise waters set against one of the most spectacular mountain ranges on the planet make for some pretty insane views.

There are a ton of awesome alpine lakes in Switzerland, but the thing that I really appreciated about these four is that they’re all relatively close together. Which means that if you only have a short time in the Swiss Alps like we did, you can still spend a decent amount of time exploring all of them. 

The town of Interlaken sits right between Lake Thun and Lake Brienz, making it a good jumping off point to explore the alps. It’s also a pretty cool town. From there, it’s a short drive and beautiful train ride from Lauterbrunnen or Grindelwald up to see Lake Fallboden. And finally, Lake Oeschinen is an easy 45 minute drive south of Interlaken. Oeschinen was probably our favorite of these four lakes—there are some super cool hikes around the lake—especially the Panorama Hike.

Definitely worth visiting one or all of these on your next trip to the Alps. As always, if you have any questions about planning a trip, don’t hesitate to comment or message me. Always happy to talk travel.

We only had seven days in Washington, so my buddy Dan and I made it a point to hit three of the best day hikes that we could find.

It was a decent amount of driving between the three, but not unreasonable, camping every night. We started with the Skyline Loop Trail in Mount Rainier at sunset, spent a day in Leavenworth and hit Colchuck, and finished with a sunrise hike to Sahale Glacier Camp in North Cascades. 

We did a bunch of other hikes too, but these were definitely the highlights. Made for an awesome way to spend a week in Washington before heading down to Oregon.

When the drive itself is just as scenic as the destination. If you’re planning a West Coast road trip for next year, save these for three of the most beautiful roads to take. I really enjoyed cruising each of them on our way to the mountains.

1. Sunrise Road, Mount Rainier National Park, Washington: A super scenic drive leading up to the Sunrise Visitor Center in Mount Rainier National Park. The road features a historic turn-off at Sunrise Park, where you can get 360-degree views of Rainier, the surrounding Cascades, and other volcanoes like Adams on a clear day. Open seasonally.

2. Cascade Lakes Scenic Byway, Oregon: It’s been called Oregon’s “Highway in the Sky,” and runs for 66 rugged miles through Deschutes and Klamath counties on the east side of the Cascade Range. There are tons of opportunities to pull off and hike the surrounding peaks and alpine lakes up there. Definitely one of my favorite drives in the US.

3. Benton Crossing Road, Eastern Sierra, California: Also sometimes called Benton Pass Road, it connects Mammoth with Benton Hot Springs. It’s popular for cycling and running, but also makes for an awesome spot to stop and take photos. You get some spectacular up-close views of the Eastern Sierra summits, as well as some good views of the north shore of Lake Crowley and the Owens River. I especially like to drive this road at sunrise and sunset, when the light is at its best. I’ve driven it in the summer and winter, and it was awesome both times.

With the 2023 hiking season winding down, I thought I’d count down some of the best hikes and travels over the past year, and share some ideas for anyone looking to travel in 2024.

If you’re heading to Switzerland next year and making the trip up to Oeschinen Lake, doing the Panorama Hike is probably the best way to make the most of the day up there.

The Oeschinensee is located at an altitude of about 5,200 feet in the Berner Oberland region of the Swiss Alps. The lake itself isn’t that big, but it’s probably one of the most spectacular and colorful alpine lakes that I’ve ever seen. You can either hike or take a gondola up to the lake, and then follow any one of the network of hiking trails from there. Out of all the trails, the Panorama Hike gives you some of the most incredible views from above the lake itself and of the surrounding peaks.

It’s about a 5 mile loop hike, with a little elevation gain, but nothing substantial. We opted to go up at sunset and then hike all the way down back to the parking lot at dusk. The trail was super quiet, as most visitors had caught the last gondola back down. This seemed like a really good way to do it.

I took this video near the highest point on the trail, which has incredible views from the lookout at the top. Definitely worth checking out next time you head to the Swiss Alps.

The other day, somebody asked me what my favorite place that I’ve traveled is.

I was nineteen the first time that I went to Alaska with my best friend. I’d never been too far outside of Upstate New York before that; I thought the landscape of the Inside Passage was just wild. Seeing those fjords and mountains for the first time kind of blew my mind. I left wanting to spend more time there.

The following summer, I went back to Alaska with the goal of finding work on a salmon boat. I had no experience at sea and I didn’t know anybody in the industry. I headed to Homer, then Haines, and just started walking the docks asking for a deckhand job. I got turned down by almost every captain in both fleets, but I kept at it. After a couple weeks of trying, I finally met a skipper who’d had a crew-member quit on him and he decided to give me a shot. I wound up working on that boat for four more summers. It was occasionally dangerous, sometimes hard work, but it was one of the best experiences that I’ve ever had. The seasonal work funded a lot of my early trips, and I got to spend every day working in the longest and deepest fjord in North America.

I’ve taken a few more trips to Alaska since then—to hike, camp, or climb. To share it with Tori, to just hang out and enjoy it. A lot’s happened since that first trip, but I don’t think that I’d be doing what I am today if we hadn’t taken it. 

Between those memories, the experiences that I had while working on the Lynn Canal, and it just being a ridiculously beautiful part of the world, I felt pretty confident in saying that Southeast Alaska is my favorite place that I’ve been. I’m hoping to make it back there really soon.
